This paper is likely to belong to the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category as it deals with natural language processing and participated in the SemEval-2018 Task 10, which is a shared task on semantic evaluation. It also uses word embeddings and pattern-based features, which are commonly used in NLP. 

It could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it uses an XGB classifier, which is a popular machine learning algorithm. 

The Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category is also a possibility as the paper deals with a supervised system for capturing discriminative attributes, which is a task that falls under the umbrella of AI. 

The Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category is another possibility as the paper deals with identifying discriminative attributes, which is a task that can be useful in information retrieval systems. 

Finally, the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category is a possibility as the paper deals with identifying attributes in word pairs, which is a task that can be useful in image captioning and other computer vision tasks.
